 cipation and labour-market strength.\n\n• Usual market effect: Stronge
 r-than-forecast jobs data is usually bullish for the local currency and 
 bearish for bonds if it increases rate-hike expectations.\n\n• Why tra
 ders care: Jobs data is a major driver of interest-rate expectations\, c
 onsumer spending expectations and recession-risk pricing.\n\n• Frequen
 cy: Monthly.\n\n• Notes: For the US\, Non-Farm Payrolls is one of the 
 most market-moving releases. For Australia\, Labour Force data is import
 ant for RBA expectations.\n\n• Acronyms: NFP = Non-Farm Payrolls\; ABS
  = Australian Bureau of Statistics\; BLS = Bureau of Labor Statistics.\n
